==English==

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|cyvylien}}, from {{der|en|fro|civilien}}. Equivalent to {{af|en|civil|-ian}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/sɪˈvɪljən/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-civilian.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# A [[person]] following the pursuits of [[civil]] life, especially one who is not an active member of the armed forces.
#* '''1858''', {{w|Prince George, Duke of Cambridge|Prince George}}, letter to {{w|Colin Campbell, 1st Baron Clyde|Sir Colin Campbell}}: 
#*: An [[army]] never can be commanded or controlled by '''civilians'''.
#: {{ux|en|Three '''civilians''' were apprehended by the soldiers and taken away in a military vehicle.}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A person who does not belong to a particular group or engage in a particular activity.
#: {{ux|en|The bathroom was for employees only, so no '''civilians''' were allowed to use it.}}
# One skilled in [[civil law]].
#* {{RQ:Swift DL4}}
#*: Ancient '''civilians''' and writers upon government.
# A [[student]] of [[civil law]] at a [[university]] or [[college]].
#* '''1788''', {{w|Richard Graves}}, ''Recollection of Some Particulars in the Life of the Late William Shenstone''
#*: although he kept his name in the college books, and changed his commoner gown to that of a '''civilian''', yet he had now, I believe, no thoughts of proceeding to any degree; and seldom resided in college any more

